              <td><strong>Thinking, Fast and Slow</strong></td>
              <td>Deep theoretical foundation on two systems of thinking</td>
              <td>UX designers, decision-makers, behavioral science students</td>
              <td>Dense; 15+ hour commitment; some priming studies questioned</td>
              <td>4/5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Predictably Irrational</strong> (Dan Ariely)</td>
              <td>Entertaining experiments on everyday irrationality</td>
              <td>Casual readers who want accessible behavioral science</td>
              <td>Less theoretical depth; more anecdotal</td>
              <td>3.5/5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Nudge</strong> (Thaler & Sunstein)</td>
              <td>Applying behavioral insights to policy and product design</td>
              <td>Product managers, policymakers, &ldquo;choice architects&rdquo;</td>
              <td>Less on psychology mechanisms; more on application</td>
              <td>3.5/5</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Influence</strong> (Robert Cialdini)</td>
              <td>Six principles of persuasion and compliance</td>
              <td>Marketers, sales professionals, copywriters</td>
              <td>Narrower scope; focused on social influence only</td>
              <td>4/5</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>Choose <strong>Predictably Irrational</strong> if you want an entertaining intro. Choose <strong>Nudge</strong> if you want practical application. Choose <strong>Influence</strong> if you're in marketing. Choose <strong>Thinking, Fast and Slow</strong> if you want the deep, foundational understanding.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Critics vs Fans -->
    <section class="review-section">
      <h2 class="review-h2">What Do Critics and Fans Say About Thinking, Fast and Slow?</h2>
      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comparison-col comparison-col-read">
          <h3 class="comparison-col-title">What Fans Say</h3>
          <ul class="review-list">
            <li>&ldquo;Permanently changed how I think about thinking&rdquo; &mdash; the most common praise across 312,000+ Goodreads ratings (4.08/5)</li>
            <li>The interactive thought experiments that make you experience your own biases are uniquely powerful</li>
            <li>A comprehensive, authoritative synthesis of decades of Nobel Prize-winning research</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="comparison-col comparison-col-skip">
          <h3 class="comparison-col-title">What Critics Say</h3>
          <ul class="review-list">
            <li>Some experiments use trick questions and artificial lab settings that don't reflect real-world reasoning</li>
            <li>The book is too long and could have been 200 pages shorter without losing substance</li>
            <li>Several cited priming studies have failed replication &mdash; the replicability crisis undermines some claims</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p><strong>The replicability debate:</strong> Kahneman's 2012 open letter acknowledging issues with priming studies was widely praised for intellectual honesty. The core biases (anchoring, availability, loss aversion) have replicated robustly. The contested studies are mainly in the &ldquo;social priming&rdquo; subfield. Critics like psychologist Daniel Kahneman's own collaborator Gary Klein have noted that the book sometimes overstates the irrationality of human judgment, ignoring the ecological validity of System 1 heuristics.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="review-section">
      <h2 class="review-h2">Frequently Asked Questions About Thinking, Fast and Slow</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">What is Thinking, Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman about?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">Thinking, Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman explains the two systems that drive how we think: System 1 (fast, intuitive, automatic) and System 2 (slow, deliberate, analytical). The book explores cognitive biases, heuristics, prospect theory, and how these mental shortcuts lead to predictable errors in judgment and decision-making.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">How many pages is Thinking, Fast and Slow?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">Thinking, Fast and Slow is 499 pages long and takes approximately 15-20 hours to read. The audiobook runs about 27 hours.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">What is the main idea of Thinking, Fast and Slow?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">The main idea is that human thought operates through two systems: System 1 is fast and intuitive but error-prone, while System 2 is slow and logical but lazy. Most cognitive errors occur because System 2 defers to System 1's quick but biased judgments.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is Thinking, Fast and Slow worth reading in 2025?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes, the core insights about cognitive biases and dual-process thinking remain foundational and widely applicable. However, some priming studies cited in the book have failed replication attempts, so readers should be aware of the replicability debate.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Who is Daniel Kahneman?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">Daniel Kahneman was a Nobel Prize-winning psychologist (2002 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences) and professor at Princeton University, renowned for his work on prospect theory, cognitive biases, and behavioral economics alongside his longtime collaborator Amos Tversky.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">What books are similar to Thinking, Fast and Slow?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">Similar books include Predictably Irrational by Dan Ariely, Nudge by Richard Thaler and Cass Sunstein, and Influence by Robert Cialdini. For a deeper dive into Kahneman's partnership with Tversky, read The Undoing Project by Michael Lewis.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Can I just read a summary of Thinking, Fast and Slow?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">A summary covers the System 1/System 2 framework and key biases, but misses the interactive thought experiments Kahneman uses to make you experience your own biases in real time. If you want to truly feel your cognitive errors, read the full book.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary class="faq-question">Is Thinking, Fast and Slow an easy read?</summary>
          <p class="faq-answer">It is accessible to general readers but requires sustained attention. The first half is engaging and intuitive; the second half on prospect theory and the two selves is denser. Expect 15-20 hours of reading time.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

